. The discoveries amassed by Humboldt and Bonpland were staggering, and much of today’s knowledge of tropical zoology, botany, geography, and geology can be traced back to Humboldt’s numerous records of these expeditions. One of these accounts, Views of the Cordilleras and Monuments of the Indigenous Peoples of the Americas, firmly established Alexander von Humboldt as the founder of Mesoamerican studies. In Views of the Cordilleras—first published in French between 1810 and 1813—Humboldt weaves together magnificently engraved drawings and detailed texts to achieve multifaceted views of cultures and landscapes across the Americas. In doing so, he offers an alternative perspective on the New World, combating presumptions of its belatedness and inferiority by arguing that the “old” and the “new” world are of the same geological age. This critical edition of Views of the Cordilleras—the second volume in the Alexander von Humboldt in English series—contains a new, unabridged English translation of Humboldt’s French text, as well as annotations, a bibliography, and all sixty-nine plates from the original edition, many of them in color.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAltamirano Rayo, Giorleny D, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aEtte, Ottmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtte, Ottmar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHumboldt, Alexander von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraft, Tobias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKutzinski, Vera M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKutzinski, Vera M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPoynter, J. Ryan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.g